            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> A new `:[bufnr]help ...` command is added that takes buffer `bufnr` and turns it into a \"secondary\" help buffer.\n\nThat will require too much \"design\" and explanation. \n\nHowever, I think your use-cases below can be addressed in a more general way:\n\n> 1\\. Plugins that wish to open a help buffer in more specific ways such as floating windows can do so more easily as well as not interfere with the user's existing windows in the process\n\nFirst of all, `nvim_open_win` and `nvim_win_set_config()` in latest nightly (Nvim 0.12) give a *lot* of control over windows/tabpages. They allow transforming to/from splits/floats, as well as moving windows anywhere.\n\nBesides that, another approach is to introduce a `:float` modifier (similar to `:vertical`) https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/31902 , and/or `:pedit` https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/9920 .\n\n> 2\\. When referencing larger pages such as `api.txt`, `lua.txt`, having multiple windows/tabs open is (subjectively) preferable to having to jump back and forth between help topics with Ctrl-O/Ctrl-I/etc.\n\n?? It's already possible to over multiple help windows showing different help buffers.",
